#: TheoryHarmony.cpp:187
msgid ""
"Listen to this tune in G major and in D major. The music may look quite "
"different, but the only difference when you listen is that one sounds higher "
"than the other. So why bother with different keys at all? Before equal "
"temperament became the standard tuning system, major keys sounded more "
"different from each other than they do now. Even now, there are subtle "
"differences between the sound of a piece in one key or another, mostly "
"because of differences in the timbre of various notes on the instruments or "
"voices involved. But today the most common reason to choose a particular key "
"is simply that the music is easiest to sing or play in that key."
msgstr ""
"Aunque las partituras sean muy distintas, al escucharlas vemos que suenan "
"prácticamente igual, sólo que una es más aguda que la otra. Entonces ¿qué "
"más da qué tonalidad se use? Antes de que se estandarizara el  uso de la "
"afinación temperada (dividir la octava en doce intervalos iguales) las "
"tonalidades mayores no sonaban todas exactamente igual. Aún hoy en día, con "
"afinación temperada, existen diferencias  sonoras debidas, fundamentalmente, "
"al timbre y tesitura de los distintos instrumentos o voces. Pero la "
"principal razón para utilizar hoy en día una determinada tonalidad es, "
"simplemente, que resulta más sencillo interpretar o cantar la partitura en "
"esa tonalidad."

